>
  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>Every interaction with an AI agent costs tokens. A typical operation — "read this file, understand the context, make this change" — carries communication overhead before the agent even starts working.</p>
  <p>Multiply that across hundreds of operations per session. The communication cost adds up.</p>

  <h2>What it looks like</h2>
  <p>You type compressed intent. The OS resolves it.</p>

  <pre><code>:compile                    # triage unstructured thinking into work items
:compile :plan :ship        # compile, plan, commit — three words, full execution
:needle add "fix auth" .p0  # file a priority-0 work item
:calibrate                  # run a retrospective on the current thread
.? status                   # what's the current state?</code></pre>

  <p>Each <code>:verb</code> resolves through the OS. The resolution is tiered:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Known verbs execute directly</li>
    <li>Learned verbs (from your usage patterns) execute with confidence weighting</li>
    <li>Unknown verbs fall back to LLM inference</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>It learns</h2>
  <p>Tack is not a fixed grammar. The OS observes your patterns across sessions and builds a vocabulary specific to your project. What you type today becomes a recognized verb tomorrow.</p>
  <p>Session 1: you type full instructions. Session 5: you type <code>:compile :plan :ship</code> and the OS knows exactly what you mean. The vocabulary persists across sessions and across agents.</p>

  <h2>Intent patterns</h2>
  <p>Beyond verbs, tack recognizes intent signals:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>You type</th><th>What happens</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>:correct X</code></td><td>Agent reverses course on X</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>:? topic</code></td><td>Answer concisely, don't execute</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>→needle</code></td><td>File a work item from current context</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.p0</code></td><td>Priority zero (highest urgency)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>CAPS</code></td><td>Boundary signal — hard constraint</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>The result</h2>
  <p>Communication gets shorter over time. The OS tracks compression in <code>ostk os metrics</code>. How much shorter depends on the project and the operator — tack adapts to how you actually work, not to a fixed grammar.</p>
</FeaturePage>
